    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Race and College Admissions</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Elliott Marc Davis letter on universities promoting 'diversity' reports that at Cornell, where he is undergraduate, racial segregation is furthered by university-sponsored ethnic-themed dorms</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Upholding Affirmative Action'' (editorial, Dec. 3), you say that ''college is often the first place that students of different races learn with and from one another.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Upholding Affirmative Action'' (editorial, Dec. 3), you say that ''college is often the first place that students of different races learn with and from one another.''</p>
        <p>At Cornell University, where I am an undergraduate, the incredible amount of racial segregation on campus is further propagated by university-sponsored ethnic-themed dorms like the Latino Living Center and Ujamaa, a dorm with an African-American theme.</p>
        <p>If universities are going to condone racial discrimination with the ''diversity'' argument, the least they can do is try to foster some sort of true diversity on campus -- not just diversity on paper.</p>
        <p>ELLIOTT MARC DAVIS  Ithaca, N.Y., Dec. 3, 2002</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
